SIMPLE: pursuit
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pursuit
<hw>Pur*suit"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>poursuite</ets>, fr. <ets>poursuivre</ets>. See <er>Pursue</er>,
<pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of following or going
after; esp., a following with haste, either for sport or in hostility;
chase; prosecution; <as>as, the <ex>pursuit</ex> of game; the
<ex>pursuit</ex> of an enemy.</as></def>
<rj><au>Clarendon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Weak we are, and can not shun <qex>pursuit</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A following with a view to reach, accomplish, or
obtain; endeavor to attain to or gain; <as>as, the <ex>pursuit</ex> of
knowledge; the <ex>pursuit</ex> of happiness or pleasure.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Course of business or occupation; continued
employment with a view to same end; <as>as, mercantile
<ex>pursuits</ex>; a literary <ex>pursuit</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Prosecution.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That <qex>pursuit</qex> for tithes ought, and of ancient time did
pertain to the spiritual court.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Curve of pursuit</b></col> <fld>(Geom.)</fld>, <cd>a
curve described by a point which is at each instant moving towards a
second point, which is itself moving according to some specified
law.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pursuivant</ent>⟦br⟧
